>> A2: In a few paragraphs, describe your code for accessing the data
>> stored in the SPT about a given page.

Since the data is lazily loaded, we rely on spt to store information about pages when they are needed to be loaded. 
Further, we do this using the help of the page fault handler. 

On a page fault, we check if the not_present flag is true that is present in the intr_frame passed to the page fault. 
If not_present is true, then it means this page fault is a candidate to load data/grow stack using spt. 

We first find the associated supplemental page table entry for the faulting address using the current threads
supplemental page table. If no spt entry is found, then this page fault could be a candidate for stack extension. 
For how we extend the stack,  please see answer to B4. If its not stack extension, then we terminate the process. 

If an spt entry is found, then this means we need to bring in the data from somwhere depending on the page type (spt_entry->vpt). 
If the page is of type ELF_TYPE (executable), then we initialize a new frame, 
link the spt_entry and frame, load the file to the page using the members in spt and finally point the 
page table entry for the faulting virtual address to the physical page. 

To elaborate on how we load th file, we use the the "file_read_at()" func in file.h to read spt_entry->file_page_size bytes
from spt_entry->file starting from spt_entry->file_offset into the page. 

If the page is of type SWAP, then the we initialize a frame, link the spt_entry to the frame,
point the page table entry for the faulting virtual address to the physical page, read the swap and
swap in the corresponding swap in the swap table using the swap index which is in the spt_entry. 



