>> A4: When two user processes both need a new frame at the same time,
>> how are races avoided?

When two processes both need a frame at the same time they will both call "init_frame()" function. 
In init_frame, we call "palloc_get_page()" which uses a lock to prevent two processes from 
quering the bitmap of free pages at the same time. 

If there are no pages available, palloc_get_page returns NULL and then we call evict frame to create space.
Inside the frame evict function, we use a lock called frame_table_lock that ensures only one process
can access the frame table at once. Moreover, it also helps avoid race conditions in evicting pages.
Once a page has been evicted, we release the lock before returning from the evict frame function. 
Back in init_frame, we obtain a new frame and do the neccesary iniatilizations. Once the new frame 
has been iniatilized, we again acquire the frame table lock to insert the new frame in the frame table. 

If a page is available, then we initialize the new frame, acquire the frame_table_lock and insert the frame to the frame_table.

Overall, using frame table locks and the lock in palloc_get_page ensures there are no race conditions 
if two processes both need a new frame at the same time.

---- RATIONALE ----

>> A5: Why did you choose the data structure(s) that you did for
>> representing virtual-to-physical mappings?

Both the supplemental page table and frame table is implemented as 
hash tables. This is for several reasons including:

There was an obvious key we could use for both the supplemental page table and
frame table. For spt, we used the uaddr as the key since the address of the 
user virtual page is unique per page. For frame table, we used the kernal virtual address
for the key since thats also unique per page. 

Using hash tables also gave us the advatange of faster searching/entry look-up 
in functions such as "get_spt_entry", "frame_evict" etc. 

Faster to delete entries in a hashtable as well. Especially useful when 
we want to reclaim pages and delete spt and frame table entries. 


