>> B2: When a frame is required but none is free, some frame must be
>> evicted.  Describe your code for choosing a frame to evict.

In our implementation, we employ the second chance algorithm for frame eviction, 
utilizing a hash table (frame_table) to store the frames.

When a frame needs to be evicted, we first acquire a lock on the frame_table to 
ensure consistency during the eviction process. We then perform up to two passes 
over the hash table to find a suitable frame. During each pass, we use a hash 
iterator to traverse the frame_table.

For each frame, we check if it is pinned. Pinned frames are those currently in 
use or otherwise protected from eviction, and thus cannot be evicted. If a frame 
is not pinned, we then check if the corresponding page has been accessed recently 
by examining the accessed bit in the page directory.

If the frame has been accessed recently, we reset the accessed bit to false, 
giving the frame a second chance to stay in memory. This means the frame will 
remain in memory for at least one more iteration of the eviction process. If 
the frame has not been accessed recently (the accessed bit is false), it is 
selected for eviction as it has not been used and is considered the best candidate 
for removal.

This process is repeated until a suitable frame is found. If no unpinned and 
unaccessed frame is identified after two passes through the hash table, we 
release the lock and return NULL, indicating that no frame can be evicted at this time.

By using this method, we ensure that frames that are actively being used are given 
a chance to remain in memory, while those that are not are evicted, thereby 
optimizing memory usage and system performance.


