>> B4: Explain your heuristic for deciding whether a page fault for an
>> invalid virtual address should cause the stack to be extended into
>> the page that faulted.

Firstly, we check if there exists a supplemental page table entry for the
address that faulted. If there does not,  this tells us that it might 
be an invalid virtual address that should cause the stack to be extended into the page that faulted. 

Before we can even validate if the faulty address should cause the stack to extend, 
we first need the esp (stack pointer). If the page fault occured becuase of user, 
we get the esp through the intr_frame that is passed to the page fault. Else,
we obtain the esp through the saved_esp member in the current thread. 

Once we have the esp, we check if the faulting address is between PHYS_BASE and esp-32. 
The stack starts at PHYS_BASE and the faulting address could occur from PHYS_BASE to esp-32
because of the PUSH/PUSHA instrucitons. PUSH/PUSHA push at most 32 bytes at once,
hence the faulting address could be between PHYS_BASE and esp-32. If the faulting address is within the
specified range mentioned, then we check if the page, that the faulty address belongs to,
doesn't exceed the stacklimit. This is a simple check and we do this by 
checking pg_round_down (fault_addr) <= PHYS_BASE - MAX_STACK_SIZE. If this is the case, 
then we extend the stack by initializing a new spt_entry with its corresponding frame. 

If any of the above check failts, we exit the process.


