>> C2: Describe how memory mapped files integrate into your virtual
>> memory subsystem.  Explain how the page fault and eviction
>> processes differ between swap pages and other pages.

Each thread has its own mappings hash table to store all the mapped files.
When mmap is called, we add the passed file into this hash table, and when
munmap is called we remove it from the hashtable and write any dirty pages back
to the original file.

When a page fault occures. We check the type of page at the fault address.

If it's a swap page:
We obtains a new frame in memory and move this page from the swap table to that
new frame.

Otherwise:
We obtain a new frame in memory and load a page from the file into that frame.

If there's no available frames then we need to evict a frame into the swap 
table to make space. In eviction:

If we're evicting a frame holding a swap page or an executable page that's dirty
we move it to the swap table. Wheras if we're evicting mapped files pages that
are dirty we write them back to the mapped file. And in both cases the frame is
freed so that it can be used.

>> C3: Explain how you determine whether a new file mapping overlaps
>> any existing segment.

In the mmap syscall handler, before allocating supplemental page entries for 
the mapped file, we loop and check if the address passed in to the syscall is
already referenced by an existing supplemental page entry (its an existing 
segment) as well as all the addresses we'll need to allocate a sup page entry 
for. If any of them are already referenced, we return -1.

---- RATIONALE ----

>> C4: Mappings created with "mmap" have similar semantics to those of
>> data demand-paged from executables, except that "mmap" mappings are
>> written back to their original files, not to swap.  This implies
>> that much of their implementation can be shared.  Explain why your
>> implementation either does or does not share much of the code for
>> the two situations.

For page faults:
Both mappings created with mmap and data demand-paged executables have the same
implementation, which is obtaining a frame, load the file page to that frame 
and then link the frame's physical address to the spt entry's user address
Therefore we put both of them in the same if condition and have them share the 
implementation code.

For frame evition:
Frames for data demand-paged from executables need to be written to the swap 
wheras the frames for mappings created with mmap need to be written back to the
original file therefore we don't have them share the same code in this case.

